description:
The canyon has some areas with pretty dark red color (similar to the nearby Red Wall Canyon) and some short sections with conglomerate narrows. The canyon is shallow (never gets high walls), but is scenic.

Nice for a not-too-long day.

Downside is the trudge up alluvial fan before you even start going up the ridge to "earn" the canyon.

Approach

Drive on North Highway (paved) to a point north of Titus Canyon and park on shoulder.

Walk a couple miles up an alluvial fan.

We took the approach that is south of Goblin (between Goblin and Grim Reaper), but if doing the fork of Goblin shown on the track (north fork), it would probably be better to do the northern approach (between Goblin and Hoodoo).

Descent

Our group didn't do the full route shown on the track that Scott Swaney uploaded. We were in the south fork, so missed the upper part of the north fork.

South Fork:

Easy downclimbs through boulders in a chute.

Wash walking

R1 40 feet from a cain down fluted conglomerate. Can be bypassed RDC.

Confluence. We walked a little way up north fork through nice conglomerate narrows.

Main canyon:

R2 20 feet from a small arch RDC.

Interesting shallow narrows.

10-foot drop over a chockstone, either partner-assist downclimb or bypass RDC.

12-foot drop - either rappel (can anchor with counterweight around boulder) or bypass RDC to an easy downclimb with 5-foot hop at bottom.

R3 80 feet from a fiddlestick off a large boulder down a vertical wall.

20-foot drop, pink and black rocks, easy walking bypass RDC

R4 40 feet from a pinch point

Beautiful red walls, canyon is really wide here.

R5 30 feet down conglomerate, from a pinch point.Bold text

Exit

Easy wash walk down to cars.
